  "prompt": "If black holes pull in all matter due to a high gravitational pull, but light has no mass and also isn't considered matter, how can black holes exist?",
  "response": "Black holes exist because they create an intense gravitational field that affects not only matter but also light, even though light has no mass. This phenomenon is explained by Einstein's theory of **General Relativity**, which describes gravity as the curvature of spacetime caused by mass and energy.\n\nHere\u2019s how it works:\n\n1. **Gravitational Pull of Black Holes**: A black hole forms when a massive star collapses under its own gravity, compressing its mass into an incredibly small region (a singularity). This creates an extremely strong gravitational field.\n\n2. **Effect on Spacetime**: According to General Relativity, mass and energy curve spacetime. The more massive an object, the more it warps the fabric of spacetime around it. A black hole warps spacetime so severely that it creates a region from which nothing, not even light, can escape. This region is called the **event horizon**.\n\n3. **Why Light is Affected**: Light follows the curvature of spacetime. Near a black hole, the spacetime curvature is so extreme that the paths of light rays (called null geodesics) are bent inward. If light gets too close to the black hole (within the event horizon), all possible paths lead inward, trapping the light and preventing it from escaping.\n\n4. **No Mass, Still Affected**: While light has no mass, it does have energy and momentum, and in General Relativity, energy and momentum contribute to the curvature of spacetime. This is why gravity affects light, even though it is massless.\n\nIn summary, black holes exist because their immense gravitational field curves spacetime to the point where even light cannot escape. This is a direct consequence of the principles of General Relativity, which describe how gravity works on both matter and light.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
